{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520573"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13218"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13218"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.01,0.82,0.04,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54226"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5652"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39703"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16195"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54226"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the rheumatology clinic with a one-year history of pain in the small joints of her hands and wrists. She experiences morning stiffness in these joints, lasting more than an hour and improving with activity. She has been taking ibuprofen which provides temporary relief from her symptoms. Her medical history is significant for a 20 pack-year smoking history. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Examination of her hands reveals symmetrical swelling of the metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints. The left index finger shows hyperextension of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint and flexion of the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint. The left little finger demonstrates flexion of the PIP joint and hyperextension of the DIP joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal an elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) of 40 mm/hr (0-20) and a C-reactive protein (CRP) of 6 mg/L (0-5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most specific serological marker for this disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-rheumatoid antibodies","Erythrocyte sedimentation rate","Anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide antibodies","Anti-double stranded DNA antibodies","Rheumatoid factor"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of rheumatoid arthritis (RA), including symmetrical small joint pain and swelling, prolonged morning stiffness, swan neck and boutonniere deformities, and elevated inflammatory markers. In this context, the question asks about the most specific serological marker for RA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-cyclic citrullinated peptide (anti-CCP) antibodies \u003C/strong\u003Eare detectable in ~60% of patients presenting with RA. This has a similar sensitivity to\u003Cstrong\u003E rheumatoid factor (RF)\u003C/strong\u003E. However, anti-CCP antibodies is the correct answer in this question, as they have slightly better specificity than RF. RF may be detected in patients with infections or in other autoimmune diseases. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR)\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-specific marker of inflammation. While it is often elevated in RA, as seen in this patient, it can be increased in many other inflammatory conditions and is not specific to RA. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-double stranded DNA antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are highly specific for SLE, not RA. They are used in the diagnosis and monitoring of SLE patients. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-rheumatoid antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are a distractor answer and do not exist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is worth noting that while anti-CCP antibodies are the most specific marker, a combination of clinical presentation, physical examination findings, imaging and various serological markers (including both anti-CCP and RF) is typically used for the diagnosis of RA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune condition causing inflammatory joint disease, most commonly affecting the small joints of the hands and feet in a symmetrical pattern.","Anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide (anti-CCP) antibodies are the most specific serological marker for rheumatoid arthritis."],"references":["L. Mathsson Alm, DL. Fountain, KK. Cadwell, et. al. The performance of anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide assays in diagnosing rheumatoid arthritis: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Clin Exp Rheumatol 2018; 36: 144-152.","D Aletaha, T Neogi, AJ Silman, et. al; 2010 Rheumatoid arthritis classifi cation criteria: an American College of Rheumatology/European League Against Rheumatism collaborative initiative. Ann Rheum Dis 2010;69:1580\u20131588."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39703"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13218"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39703"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-01T16:33:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-01T16:35:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5